<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="97" type="description">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="97">Culture characteristics.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="97">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="97">Cultures</emphasis>
are initially white with hazel at the centre, growing fast up 9 cm in diam. after 3 days, becoming honey to hazel from the edge to centre after 7-10 days. In reverse, the cultures are the same as the upper colour after 3 days, becoming cinnamon from the edge to centre after 7-10 days. 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="97">Colonies</emphasis>
are 
<normalizedToken originalValue="ﬂat">ﬂat</normalizedToken>
, sparse at the centre and compact to the margin. 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="97">Pycnidia</emphasis>
distributed radially on colony surface.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="97" type="habitat">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="97">Habitat and distribution.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="97">
Known from 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Betulaceae" genus="Corylus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Corylus mandshurica" order="Fagales" pageId="0" pageNumber="97" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="mandshurica">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="97">Corylus mandshurica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in Mount Dongling, China.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="97" type="notes">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="97">Notes.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="97">
<taxonomicName authorityName="H. Y. Zhu &amp; X. L. Fan" authorityYear="2020" class="Sordariomycetes" family="Valsaceae" genus="Cytospora" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Fungi" lsidName="Cytospora coryli" order="Diaporthales" pageId="0" pageNumber="97" phylum="Ascomycota" rank="species" species="coryli">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="97">Cytospora coryli</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is associated with canker disease of 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Betulaceae" genus="Corylus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Corylus mandshurica" order="Fagales" pageId="0" pageNumber="97" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="mandshurica">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="97">Corylus mandshurica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in China. The only strain CFCC 53162 representing 
<taxonomicName authorityName="H. Y. Zhu &amp; X. L. Fan" authorityYear="2020" class="Sordariomycetes" family="Valsaceae" genus="Cytospora" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Fungi" lsidName="Cytospora coryli" order="Diaporthales" pageId="0" pageNumber="97" phylum="Ascomycota" rank="species" species="coryli">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="97">Cytospora coryli</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
clusters as a single lineage and appears mostly related to 
<taxonomicName genus="C." lsidName="C. euonymicola" pageId="0" pageNumber="97" rank="species" species="euonymicola">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="97">C. euonymicola</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Celastraceae" genus="Euonymus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Euonymus kiautschovicus" order="Celastrales" pageId="0" pageNumber="97" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="kiautschovicus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="97">Euonymus kiautschovicus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and to 
<taxonomicName class="Sordariomycetes" family="Valsaceae" genus="Cytospora" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Fungi" lsidName="Cytospora gigalocus" order="Diaporthales" pageId="0" pageNumber="97" phylum="Ascomycota" rank="species" species="gigalocus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="97">Cytospora gigalocus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Juglandaceae" genus="Juglans" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Juglans regia" order="Fagales" pageId="0" pageNumber="97" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="regia">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="97">Juglans regia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.1016/j.funbio.2014.12.011" author="Fan, XL" journalOrPublisher="Fungal Biology" pageId="0" pageNumber="97" pagination="310 - 319" refId="B9" refString="Fan, XL, Hyde, KD, Liu, M, Liang, YM, Tian, CM, 2015a. Cytospora species associated with walnut canker disease in China, with description of a new species C. gigalocus. Fungal Biology 119: 310 - 319, DOI: https://doi.org/10.1016/j.funbio.2014.12.011" title="Cytospora species associated with walnut canker disease in China, with description of a new species C. gigalocus." url="https://doi.org/10.1016/j.funbio.2014.12.011" volume="119" year="2015 a">Fan et al. 2015a</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.3767/persoonia.2020.45.01" author="Fan, XL" journalOrPublisher="Persoonia" pageId="0" pageNumber="97" pagination="1 - 45" refId="B8" refString="Fan, XL, Bezerra, JDP, Tian, CM, Crous, PW, 2020. Cytospora (Diaporthales) in China. Persoonia 45: 1 - 45, DOI: https://doi.org/10.3767/persoonia.2020.45.01" title="Cytospora (Diaporthales) in China." url="https://doi.org/10.3767/persoonia.2020.45.01" volume="45" year="2020">2020</bibRefCitation>
) (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 2" captionStartId="F7" captionText="Figure 2. Phylogram of Cytospora, based on combined ITS, LSU, act, rpb 2, tef 1 - α and tub 2 genes. The MP and ML bootstrap support values above 50 % are shown at the first and second positions, respectively. Thickened branches represent posterior probabilities above 0.95 from the BI. Ex-type strains are in bold. Strains from the current study are in blue." figureDoi="10.3897/mycokeys.62.47854.figure2" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/375794" pageId="0" pageNumber="97">2</figureCitation>
). 
<taxonomicName authorityName="H. Y. Zhu &amp; X. L. Fan" authorityYear="2020" class="Sordariomycetes" family="Valsaceae" genus="Cytospora" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Fungi" lsidName="Cytospora coryli" order="Diaporthales" pageId="0" pageNumber="97" phylum="Ascomycota" rank="species" species="coryli">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="97">Cytospora coryli</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
differs from 
<taxonomicName genus="C." lsidName="C. euonymicola" pageId="0" pageNumber="97" rank="species" species="euonymicola">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="97">C. euonymicola</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by its larger locules (1550-1710 vs. 1150-1400 
<normalizedToken originalValue="µm">µm</normalizedToken>
) and larger conidia (5-7 
<normalizedToken originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
1-2 vs. 4.5-5 
<normalizedToken originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
1 
<normalizedToken originalValue="μm">μm</normalizedToken>
) (
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.3767/persoonia.2020.45.01" author="Fan, XL" journalOrPublisher="Persoonia" pageId="0" pageNumber="97" pagination="1 - 45" refId="B8" refString="Fan, XL, Bezerra, JDP, Tian, CM, Crous, PW, 2020. Cytospora (Diaporthales) in China. Persoonia 45: 1 - 45, DOI: https://doi.org/10.3767/persoonia.2020.45.01" title="Cytospora (Diaporthales) in China." url="https://doi.org/10.3767/persoonia.2020.45.01" volume="45" year="2020">Fan et al. 2020</bibRefCitation>
), 
<taxonomicName genus="C." lsidName="C. coryli" pageId="0" pageNumber="97" rank="species" species="coryli">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="97">C. coryli</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
differs from 
<taxonomicName genus="C." lsidName="C. gigalocus" pageId="0" pageNumber="97" rank="species" species="gigalocus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="97">C. gigalocus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by its smaller locules (1550-1710 vs. 1630-2180 
<normalizedToken originalValue="µm">µm</normalizedToken>
) with single ostiole (one to five ostioles in 
<taxonomicName genus="C." lsidName="C. gigalocus" pageId="0" pageNumber="97" rank="species" species="gigalocus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="97">C. gigalocus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
) and the larger size of conidia (5-7 
<normalizedToken originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
1-2 vs. 4.6-5.6 
<normalizedToken originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
0.8-1.3 
<normalizedToken originalValue="μm">μm</normalizedToken>
) (
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.1016/j.funbio.2014.12.011" author="Fan, XL" journalOrPublisher="Fungal Biology" pageId="0" pageNumber="97" pagination="310 - 319" refId="B9" refString="Fan, XL, Hyde, KD, Liu, M, Liang, YM, Tian, CM, 2015a. Cytospora species associated with walnut canker disease in China, with description of a new species C. gigalocus. Fungal Biology 119: 310 - 319, DOI: https://doi.org/10.1016/j.funbio.2014.12.011" title="Cytospora species associated with walnut canker disease in China, with description of a new species C. gigalocus." url="https://doi.org/10.1016/j.funbio.2014.12.011" volume="119" year="2015 a">Fan et al. 2015a</bibRefCitation>
). Based on morphology and sequence data, we describe it as a new species.
</paragraph>
